25|$|Between March 31 and April 6, 1977, 59 {{individuals}} developed type B botulism. All ill persons {{had eaten}} {{at the same}} Mexican restaurant in Pontiac, Michigan and all had consumed a <b>hot</b> <b>sauce</b> made with improperly home-canned jalapeño peppers, either by adding it to their food, or by eating a nacho that had had <b>hot</b> <b>sauce</b> used in its preparation. The full clinical spectrum (mild symptomatology with neurologic findings through life-threatening ventilatory paralysis) of type B botulism was documented.|$|E
